<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="489" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[491,1519,838,1207]" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">
Diagnosis (Female) — Prodorsum weakly to strongly wrinkled or folded medially, can also appear like areolae, laterally with elongated cells forming a reticulation, opisthosoma smooth or wrinkled between setae 
<emphasis box="[782,840,907,931]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">c1-c1</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[895,953,907,931]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">e1-e1</emphasis>
with weak to strong V-shaped folds posterior to 
<emphasis box="[491,550,941,965]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">
e1- 
<geoCoordinate box="[525,550,941,965]" degrees="1, 3" direction="east" orientation="longitude" pageId="7" pageNumber="489" precision="5555" value="1.3">e1</geoCoordinate>
</emphasis>
, 3 pairs of dorsocentral setae different in shape to dorsolateral setae 
<emphasis box="[1306,1318,941,965]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">f</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1318,1327,941,965]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">2</emphasis>
present) (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="8.[119,186,1864,1885]" captionTargetBox="[247,1355,318,1809]" captionTargetId="figure-2@8.[231,1367,318,1811]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 5 Brevipalpus lewisiMcGregor – Female: A – dorsal view; B – opisthogaster; C – sermatheca; Deutonymph: D – dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5399540" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5399540/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">Fig 5A</figureCitation>
); spermatheca terminating into a small rounded vesicle with a series of short projections and clear internal “bubble” (
<figureCitation box="[815,898,1011,1035]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="8.[119,186,1864,1885]" captionTargetBox="[247,1355,318,1809]" captionTargetId="figure-2@8.[231,1367,318,1811]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 5 Brevipalpus lewisiMcGregor – Female: A – dorsal view; B – opisthogaster; C – sermatheca; Deutonymph: D – dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5399540" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5399540/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">Fig 5C</figureCitation>
); genital and ventral shields with reticulations forming transverse bands (
<figureCitation box="[694,778,1045,1069]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="8.[119,186,1864,1885]" captionTargetBox="[247,1355,318,1809]" captionTargetId="figure-2@8.[231,1367,318,1811]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 5 Brevipalpus lewisiMcGregor – Female: A – dorsal view; B – opisthogaster; C – sermatheca; Deutonymph: D – dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5399540" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5399540/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">Fig 5B</figureCitation>
); palp femur seta slender, tapered and barbed; tarsus II with one solenidion (
<bibRefCitation author="Beard J. J. &amp; Ochoa R. &amp; Bauchan G. R. &amp; Trice M. D. &amp; Redford A. J. &amp; Walters T. W. &amp; Mitter C." box="[622,822,1080,1104]" pageId="7" pageNumber="489" refId="ref15669" refString="Beard J. J., Ochoa R., Bauchan G. R., Trice M. D., Redford A. J., Walters T. W., Mitter C. 2015 b. Flat Mites of the World. Available from: http: // idtools. org / id / mites / flatmites / (AccessedonFeb 2015)" type="url" year="2015">
Beard 
<emphasis box="[688,754,1080,1104]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">et al.,</emphasis>
2015b
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hao D. - J. &amp; Su P. &amp; Pfammatter J. &amp; Liu Q. &amp; Fan B. - Q. &amp; Wang Y. &amp; Gu T. Z." box="[833,1006,1080,1104]" pageId="7" pageNumber="489" pagination="34 - 40" refId="ref16628" refString="Hao D. - J., Su P., Pfammatter J., Liu Q., Fan B. - Q., Wang Y., Gu T. Z. 2016. Morphological and genetic characteristics of Brevipalpus lewisi (Acari: Tenuipalpidae) and comparison with other Brevipalpus species. International Journal of Acarology, 42 (1): 34 - 40. doi: 10.1080 / 01647954.2015.1114022" type="journal article" year="2016">
Hao 
<emphasis box="[885,932,1080,1104]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">et al</emphasis>
., 2016
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[491,1519,838,1207]" box="[531,1498,1114,1138]" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">
Deutonymph — Prodorsum with setae 
<emphasis box="[951,1008,1114,1138]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">sc1-2</emphasis>
broadly lanceolate. Opisthosoma with setae
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[491,1519,838,1207]" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">
<emphasis box="[491,516,1149,1173]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">c3</emphasis>
and the 4 pairs of caudolateral setae 
<emphasis box="[922,934,1149,1173]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">f</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[933,942,1149,1173]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">2</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[956,976,1149,1173]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">f3</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[990,1017,1149,1173]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">h2</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[1030,1057,1149,1173]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">h1</emphasis>
) broadly lanceolate and about as long as intervals between them, rest minute and smooth or slightly serrate (
<figureCitation box="[1210,1291,1183,1207]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="8.[119,186,1864,1885]" captionTargetBox="[247,1355,318,1809]" captionTargetId="figure-2@8.[231,1367,318,1811]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 5 Brevipalpus lewisiMcGregor – Female: A – dorsal view; B – opisthogaster; C – sermatheca; Deutonymph: D – dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5399540" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5399540/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">Fig 5D</figureCitation>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Beard J. J. &amp; Ochoa R. &amp; Bauchan G. R. &amp; Trice M. D. &amp; Redford A. J. &amp; Walters T. W. &amp; Mitter C." box="[1308,1485,1183,1207]" pageId="7" pageNumber="489" refId="ref15669" refString="Beard J. J., Ochoa R., Bauchan G. R., Trice M. D., Redford A. J., Walters T. W., Mitter C. 2015 b. Flat Mites of the World. Available from: http: // idtools. org / id / mites / flatmites / (AccessedonFeb 2015)" type="url" year="2015">
Beard 
<emphasis box="[1352,1404,1183,1207]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">et al.</emphasis>
, 2015b
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[491,1521,1252,1587]" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">
Hosts and localities — In 
<collectingCountry box="[812,871,1252,1276]" name="Israel" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">Israel</collectingCountry>
it was collected from “Blue Serbian vines”, at Nachshonim (
<bibRefCitation author="Bytinski-Salez H." box="[499,720,1287,1311]" pageId="7" pageNumber="489" pagination="15 - 48" refId="ref15869" refString="Bytinski-Salez H. 1966. An annotated list of insects and mites introduced into Israel. Israel Journal of Entomology, 1: 15 - 48." type="journal article" year="1966">Bytinski-Salez, 1966</bibRefCitation>
), but could not be found again till recently in Mizpe Ramon on petit vardo leaves. Other overseas hosts are: lemon, walnut, Boston ivy, grape, pistachio, pomegranate, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Dawn Redwood)" baseAuthorityName="Dawn Redwood" box="[491,837,1356,1380]" class="Pinopsida" family="Cupressaceae" genus="Metasequoia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="7" pageNumber="489" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[491,635,1357,1380]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">Metasequoia</emphasis>
(Dawn Redwood)
</taxonomicName>
and many ornamental plants (
<bibRefCitation author="Jeppson L. R. &amp; Keifer H. H. &amp; Baker E. W." box="[1161,1352,1356,1380]" pageId="7" pageNumber="489" refId="ref16988" refString="Jeppson L. R., Keifer H. H., Baker E. W. 1975. Mites injurious to economic plants. University of California" type="book" year="1975">
Jeppson 
<emphasis box="[1239,1293,1356,1380]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">et al.</emphasis>
, 1975
</bibRefCitation>
). It was also reported from 
<collectingCountry box="[651,739,1390,1414]" name="Algeria" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">Algeria</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[750,850,1390,1414]" name="Australia" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">Australia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[862,962,1390,1414]" name="Bulgaria" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">Bulgaria</collectingCountry>
, 
